By the time Cobb liberated Saito, all of the dreams up to the "real world" had collapsed (as the "hosts" of each dream had woken up), so they had no "higher layer" to wake up into, only the real world.

author: @krdoug82
processed_text: The constitutional amendment he calls for should be one that eliminates the Federal government’s ability to intervene in the economy.  The federal gov’t should not be able to make any decisions about what/how individuals produce or trade.  Lobbying would move to the state level, but at least then individuals and businesses would be free to move away from abusive states.

author: @krdoug82
processed_text: I like the idea Lessig presents of attacking the root of the problem, but the problem he identifies (money in politics) is not the root. The root of the problem is that congress has the power to arbitrarily take property from and restrict the liberty of the citizens of this country. Therefore, capping contributions would only mean that there will be a larger number of lobbists, and majority rules--not justice or individual liberty--will be the pricinciple guiding the actions of government.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text: @siwasher67 I'm sure money would still have an influence, but I doubt it would always be the top two funded candidates that would make it into the general.  After you change the voting system it would be so much more easier to organize.  I think you can change the voting system first and then get the CFR amendment passed a lot easier and quicker than just starting with getting the amendment passed.  At least try to do it concurrently.

author: @HebaruSan
processed_text:
@Mutex50 I agree with you that Lessig is bizarrely optimistic about the outcome of a constitutional convention; if anything, the state legislatures are even more bought and paid for than Congress at this point, and they'd probably be nominating the delegates if it even got started at all (which it won't). Let's just say that isn't my "preferred remedy."

What would stop big money from corrupting the Greens and all the other third parties down the line, in your vision?

author: @Mutex50
processed_text:
@HebaruSan Changing the voting system state by state is going to be much easier than amending the Constitution.  Also, changing the voting system will help us amend the constitution.  The reason money is a problem in politics is because it makes the Republicans and Democrats the default candidates and you have to vote for one of them to prevent the other one from getting elected. 

If we do a constitutional convention now, the corporations will just co-opt it and make it worst.

author: @y0nd3r
processed_text: Lol @26:07.....As swipe fees....audience didn't get it.

author: @HebaruSan
processed_text: @Mutex50 But it's the money that ensures that the two choices are both evils. A two-party system would be fine if either or both of those parties presented good options in line with the will of the population. The same forces that now narrow down our choices in the party primaries today could easily operate in one big open primary. Not to mention the legalized bribery of campaign contributions that influence elected officials (of whatever party) between their elections.

author: @Mutex50
processed_text: Money in politics is a problem, but the biggest problem is our voting system that forces us to vote for the lesser of two evils. We need to have an open primary with approval voting and let the top two face off in the general election.

author: @MarkoKraguljac
processed_text: Nice attempt at systematization, which assumes that we are rational and that complaint is just that and not tied in with anything else. It might work for consumer complaints or dealing with strangers. My opinion is that it wouldn't work for 99.99% of interpersonal problems. What we call complaint is ~90% something else, like: insecurities, power and responsibility issues, attention drawers, projections or plain inertia. Also, it needs effort, emotional maturity, objectivity, knowing thyself X2.

author: @kimchidreams
processed_text:
After watching this, I became very inspired and realized that I can really relate to Lady Gaga. 
When I was younger, I was called ugly. It stuck. 
Even as a baby, people would see me and think that I was ugly.
But, through the eyes of my mother, I was a beautiful child.
It was her belief that I would grow into my large nose, eyes, mouth, and ears and become beautiful like Julia Roberts.
Now that I'm 16, I've been called pretty by many, but I have trouble believing them. Thanks to Gaga, I can.

author: @TheOneLifeRider
processed_text: @avittix I agree with you with the image he's presenting. I have followed him for the past three years ever since I read his four hour work week book (I know...) and he posted this experiment on his blog long ago. What he's saying is not gaining 30lbs per month on and on, but simply reaching our genetic potential with the least amount of work and time. He didn't come up with it. There have been such experiments done in the late seventies apparently. He simply repeated the experiment.

author: @TheOneLifeRider
processed_text: @avittix Additionally in the video, around the 42 minute he says again that he's not the expert here. He's very humble but very effective, and to me credible. Thank you.

author: @TheOneLifeRider
processed_text: @avittix Hi Mate, I can understand where you'r coming from, and can relate to it. Many things he has to say sound incredible and similar to a lot of garbage that can be found everywhere. And here is why I do pay attention to what he says: he is a practical experimenter and puts to the test everything he talked about, and furthermore, he gives credit where it is due. Just after the contents in the book there is a page listing 76 people that he consulted for the contents of the book.

processed_text: @rationalperspective everyone i know who is following his stuff is getting unprecedented results for them. processed_text: @petklawi and it definately is.     I just finished 3 weeks and of course I stopped counting daily calories but have 'checked in' just to see how many i am eating on average. author: @KharonHirons
processed_text:
Very cool! =^__^=
I see a problem with the zoom-function. First you show it being controlled with the tilt-motion and later it seems to be a pinch gesture, whereas the tilt has become the crop-function. Better keep the tilt-motion the zoom and make the shake the crop-function, whilst the pinch is the framing. I can imagine a good path to go would be, designing the tilt as dimensional-regulatory control, the shake as a trigger and the finger as the tool.

Continuity makes a good continuum =^__^=
